The typical magician, however, is aware of what downfall we suffer because we're not allowed to use our pets on raids. Wizards have low-resist spells that help them land spells more. We don't. In Hate, just trying to land any nukes, I kept getting partially resisted so they only took 100 or 200 points of 600. I couldn't use my pet to deal any damage, so I got to sit there and go 'duh'. And while I shouldn't, I got aggrivated when I felt I wasn't doing my job, and someone pointed out how easy it must be, to be able to sit on a raid and do next to nothing, and reap the rewards. I didn't WANT to sit and do nothing. I wanted to kick some Arse! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Due to the raid scene, and how badly our pets are mistrusted, we often don't have a choice but to sit there with Call of the Hero and the Mod Rods, because overall, we can't contribute otherwise. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 357<br> <font color=#333333>(12/10/01 8:00:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=53.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Let the fish tank settle down first please...</span><hr size=1> Right now my machine barely runs the upgrade, not even Luclin, so I have been playing a Melee twink until I get my new machine and Luclin running, but....some observations.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Mages were never useless:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  All the way through 50th level, mages rock.  At 49-50, one could easily argue that we are relatively overpowered, and prior to Kunark, this is a strong argument.  At 58th level, pre-Luclin, I have almost never found myself to be useless, all the way through Halls of Testing, Dragon Necropolis, Kael Arena, or even Vindicator.  I cannot use pets everywhere, it is true, but do so in almost dungeons I do regularly: Sebilis, Chardok, Velketors, Howling Stones, and so on.  There is bad pathing, and I can minimize its effects generally.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Who knows how this will all shake out?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  There is a LOT of new material here: skills, spells, zones, monsters, items, and so on.  Who here claims to know how this all works out?  Especially with all the bugs, fixes, and patches yet to come.  What little I have seen indirectly is quite cool.  That summoned suit of plate is quite nice.  A gnome mage was giving away summoned armor in Oasis, and after modelling it for him, gave the suit to my skeleton pet to wear.  At 18th level, my Shadow Knight's skeleton pet is green, but with a suit of Phantom Plate, he could tank a yellow Deepwater Crocodile while I lifetap and so on.  Very cool.  I expect the skills will have a profound effect on the game, and I am waiting for these.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> /pet hold:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Well, I can understand that the majority of magicians are likely to be disappointed with this, primarily because of its high level and difficulty to attain.  I do think Verant needs to articulate clearly to us exactly why they believe Magicians to be still overpowered, although I suspect it is because they overestimate the utility of pets, or think they know something that we don't know.  Still no solution to bad pathing, which pops up in the oddest places (like the Shore of Oasis even), and effects everyone, not just Magicians.  /pet hold appears to address AOE, not pathing or AI.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Player Skill versus Design Flaws:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Documented Flaw = Feature.  User Workarounds = Marketable Skill Set.  Put out some lousy but popular software.  Some people learn to cope with the numerous flaws, and are considered skilled. This is the MicroSoft theory of software design, and it is followed by many software companies, including Verant.  Pathing is a poor mechanism to begin with, but has become central to how the game works, including game balance.  Because some people have learned to cope, Verant ignores the issue.  Luclin does not address bad pathing.<br>
<br>
Sometime this week I will be on Luclin and playing my Mage again, and I should have more intelligent things to say then.<br>
<br>
